1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 (5... c6 {Is the other
main move whitch transpose to Semi-Slav}) 6. e4 ({If} 6. e3 {then} a6 7. Bxc4
Rb8 $1 {Black will play b5 and Bb7 and has a decent position.}) 6... a6 $1 7.
Bxc4 (7. Bf4 b5 8. Nxb5 axb5 9. Qxa8 {leads to a forced draw with repetition
of moves} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 (10. Nd2 e5 {Black has a dangerous initiative.}) ({or} 
10. Kd1 e5) 10... Nb6 11. Qc6+ Bd7 12. Qb7 Bc8 13. Qc6+ Bd7 {1/2 (13) Karpov,A
(2745)-Polgar,J (2670) Dortmund 1997}) (7. e5 $6 {Is just bad} Nd5 8. Qxc4 Nb4
9. Qb3 c5 {With an advatage for Black.}) 7... Rb8 (7... b5 $2 {is not working
here.} 8. Bxb5) (7... c5 {Is premature} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e5 Ng4 10. Be2 $1 $16 {
And despite the fact that f2-pawn is hanging, White is much better.}) (7... c6
$5 {is interesting option when White's best option is} 8. Be2 $1 (8. Qc2 c5 $1)
(8. Qd1 $6 b5) 8... b5 9. Qc2 c5 (9... Bb7 10. e5 Nd5 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. O-O {
with stable advantage for White.}) 10. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 11. e5 Ng4 12. Ne4 Be7 13.
O-O Bb7 14. Bf4 Rc8 15. Qb1 $14 {It seems to me that White has a slightly
better position}) 8. Qc2 ({After} 8. Qd1 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. e5 (10. Bg5 c5) (10.
O-O c5) 10... Nd5 11. Ng5 $6 (11. a4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 b4 $1) (11. O-O Be7 12. a4
bxa4 13. Rxa4 c5) 11... Bb4 12. Qf3 Qe7 $15 {Black obtains a comfortable
position.}) 8... b5 {White is on a crossroad here. All his options deserve
serious attention.} 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 {The drawback of this move is that e4 pawn
is not very well defended.[%csl Re4]} Bb7 10. e5 (10. O-O $6 {is just a blunder
} b4 11. e5 bxc3 12. exf6 cxb2 13. Bxb2 (13. fxg7 $2 {black has amazing
resource :} bxa1=N $3 $19 (13... bxa1=Q $2 14. gxh8=Q $16)) 13... Nxf6 14. Ne5
Be7 15. Qa4+ Nd7 16. Bc3 f6 {White doesn't have any compensation for the
missing pawn. Furthermore, the d4-pawn is rather weak.}) (10. a3 $6 {is too
slow} c5 $15 {Black manages to develop his pieces in a comfortable way.}) 10...
Nd5 {In this position, White's best attempt to develop the initiative is} 11.
Bg5 $1 ({After} 11. O-O {Black goes for the typical} c5 12. dxc5 (12. Bg5 Qb6
13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Rac1 h6 15. Bh4 c4 16. Qd2 g5 17. Bg3 Be7 18. Ne1 h5 19. h3
Rd8 20. Nc2 Bb7 21. Qe3 h4 22. Bh2 Rg8 $13 {0-1 Zsinka,L-Kallai,G/ HUN 1999/
EXT 2000 (37)}) (12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Be3 c4 14. Ng5 Be7 15. Ne4 Nb6 16. f4 Qd7
17. a3 Qc6 18. Bf3 O-O) 12... Bxc5 $1 13. Ne4 (13. Bg5 Qc7 $1 14. Rac1 (14. Ne4
$140 Bxf2+ $19) 14... Nb4 $17 {[%csl Re5]}) 13... Rc8 (13... Be7 $5) 14. Nxc5
Rxc5 15. Qb1 Ne7 $132 {[%csl Re5]}) (11. Ne4 c5 ({Also possible is} 11... Nb4
12. Qb1 c5) 12. Bg5 Qb6) 11... Be7 $1 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Qxc7 Qb4+
15. Qc3 Qxc3+ 16. bxc3 Nb6 {Black enjoys a typical positional compensation for
the missing pawn since the c3-pawn could be easily attacked. Later on, he is
going to play Ke7 followed by doubling on the c-file.[%csl Rc3]}) (9. Bb3 {The
bishop is in danger here} c5 $1 {[%csl Rb3]} 10. Bf4 (10. dxc5 Nxc5 {And Black
will enjoy the advantage of the pair of bishops.}) 10... c4 11. Bxc4 bxc4 12.
Bxb8 Nxb8 13. d5 Nbd7 $1 $13 {Later on, Black develops his bishops on e7 and
b7 and enjoys a big advantage.}) 9... Bb7 10. e5 ({Too slow seems to be} 10.
O-O {Black should carry out the typical c7-c5 pawn advance. As the reader
could see on a number of occasions, white queen is rather vulnerable on the
c-file. The game may continue} c5 11. Bf4 (11. d5 Qc7) 11... Rc8 12. d5 c4 $1
$10 {After this precise move, Black overtakes the initiative. Already, his
bishop could be developed on the b4-square. After} 13. Be2 exd5 14. Rad1 (14.
exd5 Bc5) 14... Bb4 15. e5 Bxc3 16. bxc3 (16. Qxc3 Ne4 17. Qa3 Qe7) 16... Ne4
17. Nd4 O-O 18. Nf5 Re8 {White should play precisely in order to keep the
equality. For example} 19. Bf3 Nxe5 20. Bxe4 Ng6 21. Nd6 Rxe4 22. Nxb7 (22.
Nxe4 Nxf4) 22... Qb6 23. Nd6 Nxf4 24. Nxc8 Qe6 25. Nd6 Re5 26. g3 Qh3 $11) (10.
Bg5 c5 $5) (10. Bf4 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc7c5,Gc8c2]}) 10... Nd5 11. Be4 (
{Wrong is} 11. Bxh7 $2 {because White loses a valuable time. The play may
continue} Nb4 12. Qb1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 c5 $17) 11... Nxc3 12. Bxb7 Rxb7 13. Qxc3 (
13. bxc3 Nb6) 13... Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Be3 (15. Qc6 Rb6 16. Qe4 Qa8 17. Qg4
Rc8) 15... Nb6 16. Rfc1 Nd5 $11 {With such a Knight on d5, only Black can be
better here.} *

