1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 {This is a very important line.
White prefers to go for a solid position instead of entering the compicated
positions which arise from the main lines. Usually when White is not ready for
the theoretical battle they will choose this line.} a6 $1 {This little move is
very important. We want to provoke a2-a4 which weakens the b4- square.} 6. a4 (
{Black has easy play after} 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 Bb7 $11 {See examples in
the game section.}) (7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Re1 b4 10. Nb1 c5 11. Nbd2 Be7
12. e4 cxd4 13. e5 Nd5 14. Ne4 O-O 15. Qxd4 Qb6 {with excellent play for black
in Ponomariov,R (2739)-Kramnik,V (2772) Moscow 2009}) 7... Bb7 $1 {And Black
develops his pieces in the optimal way.[%cal Gb8d7,Gc7c5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]}) 6... b6
$5 {interesting try to complicate position and play for a win} (6... c5 7. Bxc4
Nc6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 (9. dxc5 $5 {Kramnik -Topalov 2009 Amber}) 9... cxd4 (
9... O-O 10. Rd1 Qc7) 10. Rd1 e5 $11 {this line has drawish reputation and my
advice is better to avoid it}) 7. Bxc4 Bb7 8. O-O $1 {White's best move order
when Black must play with care. First of all, White finishes the development
and later he will decide whether to put the queen on e2 or b3.} ({The immediate
} 8. Qe2 {is not dangerous. the idea e3-e4 could be prevented by means of[%cal
Ge3e4]} Bb4 9. O-O O-O (9... Nbd7 $6 10. Bd3 c5 11. Na2 $14) 10. Rd1 (10. Bd3
c5 11. dxc5 ({Now} 11. Na2 {could be met by the typical} Nc6 {That's why it is
not desirable to go for the premature Nbd7.}) 11... Bxc5 12. e4 Nbd7 $1 {[%cal
Gd8c7,Ga8c8,Gf8d8]} (12... Nfd7 13. e5) 13. Bg5 ({The attempt to prevent Black
from playing Qc7 by} 13. Bf4 {is well met by} Nh5 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Rac1 (15. g3
Nhf6 16. Rac1 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Qc5) 15... Nf4 {With more than comfortable
position for Black.}) ({Weak is} 13. e5 {because after} Bxf3 {White's pawn
structure will be spoiled.}) 13... Qb8 14. Rad1 Rc8 {With an equality.} (14...
Ne5 15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 $11 {1/2 (28) Bacrot,E (2692)
-Bluebaum,M (2580) Emsdetten GER 2016})) 10... Nbd7 $1 {This is the right
place for the Knight. Black's idea is to prepare c7-c5} 11. Bd3 ({Doesn't
create problems} 11. Ne5 Qe7 (11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4) 12. Nd3 (12. f4
Rfd8 13. Bd2 c5) 12... Ba5 13. f3 c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 $11 {With an equal position.
}) 11... c5 12. dxc5 (12. Na2 Ba5 13. e4 Qc7 14. dxc5 bxc5 $11) 12... Bxc5 13.
h3 Qc7 14. Bd2 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. e4 Rfd8 {In this position, Black even
enjoys a slight advantage because of his active pieces. 0-1 (37) Olafsson,H 
(2549)-Ghaem Maghami,E (2596) Berlin GER 2015}) 8... c5 $1 {This is the most
precise move. If Black develops his bishop via b4, then White will attack it
by means of Qb3. Otherwise, the idea to gain space in the centre by playing
Qe2 followed by e3-e4 and even e5 looks very dangerous. Thats's why all other
moves are dangerous for Black.} (8... Bb4 9. Qb3 Qe7 (9... Be7 10. Ne5 O-O 11.
Rd1 Nbd7 12. f3) 10. e4 $1 {White opens the position in order to use his lead
in the development.} Nxe4 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nxe4 12. Re1) 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12.
Bg5 $1 $146 Qd6 13. Rfe1 $1 Bxe1 14. Rxe1 Bxf3 15. Bxe6 O-O 16. Bxf7+ Rxf7 (
16... Kh8 17. Be7 Qf4 18. Bxf8 Nc6 19. Qxf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 Rxf8 21. d5 h6 22.
Be6 Nd4 23. Kg2 Nxf3 24. Rc1 $18) 17. Re8+ Qf8 18. Rxf8+ Kxf8 19. gxf3 $16 {
White has serious winning chances.[%cal Gg5h4,Gh4g3,Gd4d5,Gd5d6]}) ({After} 
8... Bd6 $6 {White could make use of the vulnerable position of the d6-bishop.}
9. Qe2 Nbd7 10. e4 e5 11. Rd1 Qe7 12. Bg5 O-O 13. Nd5 {With a huge advantage.})
(8... Nbd7 9. Qe2 $1 Bb4 (9... c5 10. Rd1 Qb8 11. Ne5 $1 Bd6 (11... Nxe5 12.
dxe5 Qxe5 13. Bb5+) 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. d5 $1) 10. Bd3 $1 c5 11. Na2 Ba5 12. e4
O-O 13. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2b4]}) 9. Qe2 ({White may simplify into
drawish endgame by playing} 9. dxc5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 11. Ne5 Nc6 12. Nxc6
Bxc6 13. b3 Ke7 14. Bb2 Bb7 $11) 9... Qc7 10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. d5 {The only way to
fight for the advantage.} ({In case of} 11. b3 cxd4 12. exd4 Bb4 {Black has a
very confortable version of IQP position since he has a firm control over the
important d5-square, while White has problems to develop a kingside initiative.
}) ({The move} 11. Ne5 {should be answered by} Bd6 $1 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. dxc5
Qc6 14. e4 Qxc5 15. Be3 Qc7 16. g3 O-O {With an equal game.}) 11... exd5 12.
Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Bxd5 14. Rxd5 Be7 15. e4 (15. b3 {is too slow} O-O 16. Bb2
Nf6 17. Rdd1 Qb7 18. Ne5 Rfd8 19. Qc4 Bf8) 15... O-O 16. Bf4 (16. e5 Qc6 17.
Rd1 Rfe8 18. Bf4 Nf8 $15 {0-1 (65) Smirnova,E (2155)-Khokhlova,D (2213) Loo
RUS 2016}) 16... Qc6 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Rfe8 19. g3 Bf8 20. Qg4 Re6 $5 $132
{Black will have a sufficient counterplay Holt,C (2533)-Azarov,S (2619)
Chicago USA 2015} (20... b5 $11) *

