1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Be7 9. Re1 (9. Qc2 {plan-2}) (9. Qe2 O-O 10. Rd1 {the most unpleasant
plan - played recently by Aronian}) (9. Ne5 {most often played} O-O 10. Qg4 Nc6
$1) 9... O-O 10. h4 $5 {The idea is Ng5 followed by Qh5[%cal Gf3g5,Gd1h5]} c5
$1 {Always when our opponent makes an attack on the kingside, we should strike
in the centre.} ({The greedy} 10... Bxh4 {leads to a difficult position for
Black after} 11. Nxh4 Qxh4 12. Re3 $40) 11. Ng5 $1 {Of course! This is the
most principled continuation.} ({Less dangerous is} 11. Bd3 Nd7 $1 {Clearly
better than 11...Nc6. Black wants first to consolidate his kingside before
attacking the center.} 12. Ng5 $6 {The logical continuation of 10.h4 but I
definitely don't like it as I didn't find any advantage for White. However,
it's the only way to justify the 10th move.} Nf6 13. Bf4 cxd4 14. cxd4 h6 15.
Be5 Bd7 $5 {This position seems to be very promising alternative for Black. I
don't see any clear path for White to develop his attack.} 16. Re3 Bc6 17. Rg3
Bd6 $1 ({Wrong is} 17... hxg5 $2 18. hxg5 Ne4 19. Qh5 Bxg5 20. Re1 {White has
a very strong pressure.}) 18. Nh7 $5 {is the main try to complicate the
position.} (18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Nh7 Qxd4 $1 {simple and strong.} (19... Nxh7 $6
20. Qg4 g5 21. hxg5 $40 {is not that clear, White has some initiative.}) 20.
Nxf8 Kxf8 $17 {is almost winning for Black. Too much material for the exchange
and not a single attacking idea for White.}) 18... Bxe5 19. dxe5 Nxh7 20. Qg4 {
The only idea for White. But now, Black can give back some material to repulse
the attack.} Ng5 {the simplest way to clarify the position.} (20... g5 21. Qh5
{threatening Bh7 and hxg5} f5 22. Qxh6 {is also good for Black but White can
still have some dreams about giving mate.}) 21. Rd1 Qe7 22. hxg5 Qxg5 23. Qe2 (
23. Qh3 Qf4 {With ...f5 to follow and White is lost.}) 23... Qh4 24. Rg4 Qe7
25. Qe3 Kh8 (25... f5 {is also possible} 26. Qxh6 (26. exf6 Rxf6 {gives
nothing to White.}) 26... Rad8 $17) 26. Qg3 f5 $17) ({Interesting was the
"positionally-active"} 11. d5 $5 exd5 12. Bxd5 Nd7 (12... Nc6 13. Ba3 {White
has a very strong pressure on the center as a compensation for the pawn.
Although, Black is not in real danger but has to be careful.}) 13. Bf4 (13. Bb3
Nb6 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. Ba3 Nd7 16. Rad1 Bf6 17. Ng5 b6 $15 {White doesn't have
enough compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Nb6 14. Be4 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 h6 {It's
not clear how White could develop his initiative.}) 11... h6 $1 $146 {It seems
that this novely solves all the problems. Logical continuation. The bishop
should be transferred to the b1-h7 diagonal.} ({It seems that after} 11... cxd4
12. Qd3 {White has dangerous initiative.}) 12. Bd3 ({In response to} 12. Qh5 {
Black could follow with} cxd4 (12... Nd7 13. Nxe6) 13. Bd3 Nc6 {Planning 14...
Qe8 followed by f7-f5. This is a very typical way to exchange the queens in
such positions.[%cal Gd8e8,Gf7f5]}) ({Too passive is} 12. Ne4 {Black is just a
healthy pawn up after} cxd4 13. cxd4 Nd7 14. d5 Nb6) ({In case of} 12. Qd3 {
Black just takes the knight} hxg5) 12... cxd4 (12... Nd7 13. Nh7 Re8 14. Qg4) (
12... hxg5 13. Qh5) 13. Bh7+ ({The other attacking idea} 13. Nh7 {is even less
dangerous.} dxc3 14. Bxh6 (14. Nxf8 Qxf8) 14... gxh6 15. Qg4+ Kh8 16. Re3 Rg8 {
And Black is winning.}) 13... Kh8 14. Bc2 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gd1f3]} Nc6 15. Qf3 ({
The move} 15. Qd3 {is well met by} f5 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Rxe6 dxc3 {When White
fails to prove any compensation for the missing material.}) ({After} 15. Nh7 {
we go for the typical exchange sacirifice after} dxc3 16. Nxf8 Qxf8 $17) 15...
f5 $1 {This is a very important idea. Black gives back one of the pawns in
order to neutralize White's initiative.} 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Rxe6 Qd7 18. Rg6 Qe8
(18... Ne5 19. Qh5 Nxg6 20. Bxh6) (18... Rf6 19. Rxf6 Bxf6 20. Bxf5) 19. Re6
Qd7 $11 {With a draw by repetition.} *

