1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Be7 9. Qc2 {This move is more dangerous than it looks at first sight.
White intends to meet 9...0-0 by means of Bd3, thus provoking Black to weaken
his kingside.} Nd7 $1 {This is the most precise move order. Black's idea is to
prevent the opponent from weakening his kingside by means of Bd3.} ({After} 
9... O-O {White could play} 10. Bd3 $5 h6 (10... f5 11. Bc4) 11. Bf4 Nd7 12.
Qd2 {when the idea to sacrifice bishop on h6 is always in the air.[%csl Rh6]})
10. Re1 ({Another option is} 10. Bf4 {when Black could develop his pieces in a
comfortable way. For example} O-O 11. Rad1 Nf6 12. Rfe1 b6 13. Ne5 Bb7 {At
this point, the idea to attack by transfering the rook via the 3rd rank} 14.
Re3 {is well met by} Nd5 15. Rh3 f5 $1 16. Bc1 Bf6 17. Re1 Qe7 18. g4 g6 {
White has no attack at all. Black is a pawn up and has an active light-squared
bishop.}) 10... O-O 11. Bf4 Nf6 (11... b6 $6 12. d5 $1 e5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14.
Bxe5 Bd6 15. Bd3 h6 16. Qa4 Bxe5 17. Rxe5 Qd6 18. Qe4 g6 19. Bb5 Bd7 20. Bxd7
Qxd7 21. Re1 Rad8 22. c4 $16) 12. Ne5 (12. Rad1 b6 13. Ne5 Bb7 14. Re3 Nd5 15.
Rh3 f5 {The most important defense idea in this line.} 16. Bc1 Bf6) 12... Nd5
13. Bg3 c5 14. Bd3 ({White can also try:} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Rad1 Qa5 16. Rd3 f6
17. Nf3 Nb6 18. Bb3 Kh8 19. Bxe6 Bxe6 20. Rxe6 Rad8 {The attack is over and
Black has a better pawn structure.}) (14. Rad1 cxd4 15. Rxd4 Qa5) 14... f5 $11
*

