1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Be7 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gd1e2]} O-O 10. Rd1 {This idea advocated by Levor
Aronian is by far White's most dangerous attacking plan in this variation.
Later on, he intends to play Ne5 followed by the manoeuvre Rd3-g3. Black
should play very precisely in order to deal with White's threats. At this
point, I recommend[%cal Gf3e5,Gd3g3,Gd1d3]} Nd7 {Black not only takes under
control the important e5-square, but at the same time is planning to play 11...
Nb6 in response to 11.Rd3.} (10... c6 {Is too slow and gives White a chance to
organize an attack by} 11. Ne5 Nd7 (11... f6 12. Nd3) 12. Rd3 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qc7
14. Rh3 {Typical rook lift. Now Qh5 is a dangerous threat.} g6 15. Qe3 h5 16.
Qe4 $16 Rd8 17. Bh6 Bd7 18. Rxh5 {Followed by Bd3 is winning for White.}) (
10... c5 11. d5) 11. Rd3 $1 ({After} 11. Ne5 $5 {which was see in our model
game - Narayanan,S (2481)-Lu Shanglei (2615) Olongapo City PHI 2015, Black's
most solid option seems to be} Nb6 ({Another interesting possibility is to
sacrifice the queen for rook, bishop and a pawn after} 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qe8
13. Rd3 Qc6 14. Rh3 Rd8 15. Bb5 Qd5 16. Ba3 Bxa3 17. Rd3 Bc5 18. Rxd5 exd5 {
With an unclear position.}) 12. Bd3 ({Less dangerous seems to be} 12. Bb3 {
White's light-squared bishop has no work on the a2-g8 diagonal.} Nd5 13. Rd3 (
13. Bd2 Bg5 14. Bc2 Bxd2 15. Rxd2 Ne7 16. Rd3 f6 17. Rh3 g6 {And White
couldn't continue developing his attack.}) 13... f6 14. Nf3 {[%cal Gc3c4]} b5 {
[%csl Gb5]} 15. a4 c6 {And Black keeps everything under control.[%cal Gc8e6]})
12... Qe8 $1 {Again, Black should employ an idea we are familiar with. Now
Black is ready to go for f7-f5 against pretty much every attack against the
h7-pawn. The play may continue} 13. Qc2 f5 14. a4 Bd6 15. Re1 c5 16. a5 Nd5 17.
Bc4 cxd4 18. cxd4 b5 19. axb6 Nxb6 20. Bb3 a5 21. Ba3 Bxa3 22. Rxa3 a4 23. Ba2
Qe7 24. Qc3 Qd6 {With approximately equal position.}) ({Too slow is} 11. Bf4
Nf6 12. Ne5 Nd5 {Since Black manages to simplify the position and parry
White's attacking ideas.} 13. Bd2 Bg5 14. Bd3 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 f6 16. Nf3 c5 {
Black's position is already preferable.}) 11... Nb6 12. Bb3 f6 $1 {It's much
more important to prevent Black from playing Ne5 then to keep the extra pawn.}
13. Re3 ({After} 13. Bxe6+ Bxe6 14. Qxe6+ {Black should play} Rf7 {His idea is
to follow with Qd5 and Re8.[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gd8d5,Ga8e8]} 15. Be3 (15. c4
Qd7 16. Qxd7 Nxd7 $11) 15... c6 16. c4 Qc8 17. Qxc8+ Rxc8 18. Rc1 Bf8 19. g3
Rd7 $11) 13... Re8 14. h3 Bd6 15. Bxe6+ Bxe6 16. Rxe6 Qd7 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18.
Qd3 Qc6 $11 {The position is equal.} *

