1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. O-O Nxc3 8.
bxc3 Be7 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Qg4 {This is White's main plan in this variation. His
idea is to bring to queen to the kingside as soon as possible. Later on, White
could continue with Bh6 followed by Re1-e3-g3 (h3).} ({In case of} 10. Qf3 {
Black should challenge the central e5-knight by means of} Nd7 11. Rd1 Bd6 12.
Bf4 {At this point, I think that Black should execute the f7-f6 advance after
the maneuvre Nb6-d5.} (12. Bd3 f5) 12... Nb6 13. Bd3 Nd5 14. Bd2 f6 {Here, the
attempt to make use of the weakened h7-pawn by means of} 15. Qh3 {is not
dangerous. The game may continue} g6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. c4 Nf4 18. Qh6 Nxd3 19.
Qxg6+ Kh8 $11 {With a prepetual.}) ({If White goes for} 10. Qh5 {, we follow
the same strategy} Nd7 {The knight should be neutralized. It's not difficult
to see that on h5, White queen doesn't stay very well.}) 10... Nc6 $1 {This is
the most flexible continuation. Black's idea is to be able to be able to play
Ne7 in some moment, thus protecting the king. For example, in case of 11.Bh6
Bf6 12.Re1, the e7-square is available for the knight and Black could follow
with 12...Ne7.} ({Worse is} 10... Nd7 {because after} 11. Bh6 Bf6 12. Rfe1 {
Black d7-knight lacks suitable squares.[%csl Rd7]}) 11. Re1 $1 {This seems to
be White's best continuation. Depending on the circumstances, he could develop
his c1-bishop either on h6 or on a3. At the same time, the option to realize a
rook-lift is open.} ({The standart idea} 11. Bh6 Bf6 12. Rfe1 {Doesn't promise
White any advantage. Black could go for the typical} Ne7 {Intending to bring
the knight to f5 and attack the centre by means of c7-c5.[%csl Gd7][%cal Gc7c5,
Gc6e7,Ge7f5]} 13. Rad1 c5 14. Rd3 (14. dxc5 Qa5) 14... b5 {Well played. The
idea to deflect the bishop from the a2-g8 diagonal looks very sound. It's not
difficult to see that the bishop will be vulnerable on the b5-square.} ({
Another possibility is to try to make use of the unprotected position of the
e1-rook by playing} 14... Qa5 $5 {This idea, however leads to a forced draw
after[%cal Ga5e1]} 15. Rf3 Nf5 16. Nxf7 cxd4 17. Rxf5 Qxf5 18. Qxf5 exf5 19.
Ne5+ Kh8 20. Nf7+ $11) 15. Bxb5 cxd4 16. Rh3 {White concentrates all his
forces on the kingside without thinking about the material. His attack,
however, could be easily stopped. For example:} (16. cxd4 Qa5 {[%csl Gb5,Ge1]})
16... Nf5 17. Bd3 dxc3 18. Nc6 Qc7 19. Bf4 Qxc6 20. Be4 Qc4 21. Bxa8 e5 {And
Black is winning. 0-1 (29) Sanikidze,T (2537)-Nisipeanu,L (2669) Gjakova KOS
2016}) ({Too slow seems to be} 11. Bf4 Nxe5 {The simplyfications will kill
White's attack.} ({Also, Black could have taken radical measure by playing} 
11... f5 {I don't believe that White's compensation for the pawn is sufficient.
}) 12. dxe5 {This is White's best chance. In the middlegame the e5-pawn gives
White a spatial advantage and increases the attacking chances.[%csl Ge5]} ({
After} 12. Bxe5 Bf6 13. Rae1 Bd7 14. Re3 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Bc6 16. Rg3 g6 {Black
doesn't have problems.}) 12... f5 $1 {Very instructive move. We should
eliminate White's spatial advantage, even by giving back our extra pawn.} 13.
exf6 Bxf6 14. Bxe6+ ({After} 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. Rd3 Kh8 16. Re1 e5 17. Qh5 g6 18.
Qe2 {White's initiative could be neutralized by means of} Be6 (18... exf4 {0-1
(36) Nguyen Duc Hoa (2508)-Vidit,S (2610) Sharjah UAE 2014}) 19. Bxe6 exf4 20.
Rd7 Qc5 {With a promising position for Black.}) 14... Bxe6 15. Qxe6+ Rf7 16.
Rad1 Qe8 {The position is equal. 1/2 (58) Wang Yue (2718)-Wojtaszek,R (2727)
Huai'an CHN 2016}) ({The positional} 11. Rb1 {is very well met by the standard}
f5 {Let's see how the play may continue.} 12. Nxc6 fxg4 13. Nxd8 Rxd8 14. Be2 {
And here Black should play} Bf6 {Preparing the advance e6-e5.[%cal Ge6e5]} (
14... c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxg4) 15. Bxg4 (15. Bf4 c5 16. dxc5 h5 17. Bd6 (17.
f3 Bxc3 18. fxg4 hxg4 $11) 17... b6 $11) 15... e5 $11) 11... f5 {Again, Black
goes for the concept we are already familiar with. In order to neutralize
White's initiative, he is ready to give back his extra pawn.} ({In case of} 
11... Bf6 12. Rb1 Ne7 {White could follow with} 13. Ba3 {Keeping some
initiative.}) 12. Qf3 ({To an equal endgame leads} 12. Nxc6 fxg4 13. Nxd8 Rxd8
14. Bxe6+ Bxe6 15. Rxe6 Bd6 $11 {1/2 (62) Vassallo Barroche,M (2381)-Levin,F 
(2511) Llucmajor ESP 2016}) 12... Nxe5 13. Rxe5 Kh8 14. Bf4 {Instead of
winning the pawn back immediately, White prefers to keep the initiative.} ({
After} 14. Bxe6 Bd6 15. Re2 Bxe6 16. Rxe6 Qd7 {Black is perfectly fine. His
next move will be c7-c5.[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5]}) ({In case of} 14. Re1 {Black
could attack the centre by means of} c5 {The position arising after} 15. Bf4
cxd4 16. Rad1 Qb6 17. cxd4 Bd7 $11 {is equal.}) ({The patient} 14. h3 $146 {
seems to be harmless. In order to finish the development and to establish
coordination, Black leaves the e6-pawn.} Bd6 15. Re2 Qh4 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gg5g4]
} 16. Bxe6 (16. Bd2 g5 $13) 16... Bxe6 17. Rxe6 Rae8 18. Rxe8 Rxe8 $11) ({
Another harmless attempt is} 14. Re2 Bd6 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qd6 $11 {With
equality.1/2 (26) Georgescu,T (2460)-Frolyanov,D (2555) Iasi ROU 2016}) 14...
Bd6 15. Rae1 $1 {This exchange sacrifice is White's best bet in his fight for
an advantage. White is planning to establish a domination on the dark-squares.
At the same time, Black lacks space and has problems to develop his
light-squared bishop.} ({In case of} 15. Re3 {Black reaches an equal endgame
by means of massive simplifications.} Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qd6 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18. Bxe6
Re8 19. Bd5 Rxe3 20. fxe3 Rb8 21. c4 b6 22. a4 g6 23. Rb1 Kg7 24. a5 Kf6 25.
Rb4 Bd7 {1/2 (53) Narayanan,S (2420) -Lu Shanglei (2533) Pune IND 2014}) 15...
Bxe5 16. Bxe5 {Now White wants to play Qh5 followed by Re3-g3. Nevertheless,
Black has enough resources to parry the attack.[%cal Gf3h5,Ge1e3,Ge3g3]} h6
$146 {This novelty solves all Black's problems. Black is ready to meet the
move 17.Qh5 by means of 17...Qg5. Also, the idea c7-c6 followed by Bd7-e8
could be considered here.[%cal Gc7c6]} (16... Rf7 17. Qh5 Kg8 18. Re3 {1-0 (65)
Ris,R (2412) -Kuzubov,Y (2638) Dubai UAE 2016}) 17. Qh5 ({Too slow is} 17. Re3
{For example} Bd7 18. Bb3 c6 19. Qe2 Kh7 20. Rg3 (20. g4 {doesn't work because
of} Qg5 21. Rg3 (21. Bc2 g6) 21... f4 {And Black is better.}) 20... Rg8 21. Qh5
Be8 {White couldn't continue the attack.}) 17... Qg5 $15 {After this last
precise move, White's attack is quite problematic. I think that all the
dangers are behind us.} *

