4... dxc4 5. Bg5 {This is by far White's main move in the position. After
pinning the knight, he intends to follow with e2-e4. Black should start
fighting for the e4-square. That's why his main option is} Bb4 6. Qa4+ {This
is one of the most popular deviations from the main line. White's idea is to
provoke the move Nc6 which prevents Black from the possibility to fight for
the centre by means of c7-c5. Nevertheless, on a4, White queen is quite
vulnerable.} (6. e4 $1 {is the main line}) (6. e3 b5 7. a4 c6 {Look game -6
Korobov-Aronian 2014}) 6... Nc6 7. e4 $6 {As usual, this active move only
gives Black objects for counterattack. In this concrete position, the d4-pawn
is quite vulnerable.} ({The moves} 7. a3 $1) ({and} 7. e3 {are dealt with in
the next analysis.}) 7... Bd7 $1 (7... a6 8. Bxc4 Rb8 9. Qd1) 8. Qc2 h6 $1 {
very important detail as White removes the pin and wantes to answer 9...b5 by
means of 10.Nxb5.} ({the immediate} 8... b5 $2 {is losing on the spott} 9. e5
h6 10. exf6 hxg5 11. fxg7 Rg8 12. Qh7 Ne7 13. Ne5 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge2h5]} c5 14.
Be2 Qc7 15. Nxf7 cxd4 16. Bh5 Bc6 17. Rd1 $18) 9. Bd2 ({Pointless is} 9. Bf4 {
since Black follows with} b5 {anyway.} 10. Rd1 $6 {This is dubious.} ({But
even after the normal} 10. Be2 a6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rad1 Ba5 {Black is a healthy
pawn up.}) 10... Ba5 11. a3 Rb8 12. Be2 (12. Ne5 Qe7) 12... b4 $19 {Black is
already winning.}) ({In case of} 9. Bh4 {Black should play} g5 {when} 10. d5 {
is not dangerous, because of} (10. Bg3 g4) 10... exd5 11. exd5 Qe7+ 12. Be2
Nxd5 {White doesn't have any compensation for the sacrificed material. The
attempt to complicate the matters by means of} 13. O-O Bxc3 14. Bxc4 {Simply
doesn't work because of} Ncb4 15. Qb3 Bg7 16. Bg3 c6 {Black is already winning.
}) ({The idea to give the dark-squared bishop is not quite appealing to me.
After} 9. Bxf6 $6 Qxf6 {Black has a pair of bishops, pawn up and pressure
against the d4-pawn.[%csl Rd4]}) 9... b5 $1 {Nevertheless! We shouldn't allow
White to comfortably develop his pieces.} 10. Nxb5 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 a6 {It turns
out that White couldn't protect his central d4-pawn.} 12. Nc3 ({weaker is} 12.
Na3 Nxd4 13. Qxc4 Bb5 14. Nxb5 axb5 15. Qc5 Qd6 16. Qxd6 cxd6 17. Bd3 Ke7 18.
O-O (18. Nf3 Nb3) 18... Nd7 $15 {With a perfecly comfortable endgame for Black.
}) 12... Nxd4 13. Qd1 c5 14. Nxc4 (14. Bxc4 Bc6 15. O-O O-O 16. f3 Qb6 17. b3
Rfd8 {0-1 (33) Iruzubieta Villaluenga,J (2414)-Horvath,C (2545) Lisbon 2001})
14... O-O 15. Bd3 Bb5 16. O-O Nd7 17. Qh5 Rb8 18. b3 Nb6 {Black is better[%csl
Rc4]} *

