1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d5 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 dxc4 5. Bg5 Bb4 6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. e3 {This
continuation is much more solid than 7.e4. White is planning to win back the
pawn without weakening so much his central squares. Now, Black should try to
make use of the ackwardly placed white queen.} Bd7 {Now White should make one
more with his queen.} 8. Qc2 {And now, Black could protect his c4-pawn by
playing the typical} b5 9. a3 $1 ({After normal development White is
struggling to prove his compensation.} 9. Be2 Rb8 10. O-O Be7 11. a4 a6 12.
axb5 axb5 {In such kind of positions, the c4-pawn makes difficult for White to
establis a coordination in his camp. At this point, a typical mistake would be}
13. b3 $6 ({Even after the normal} 13. Ne5 O-O 14. Bf3 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd5 16.
Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Bxd5 Qxe5 19. Be4 g6 {Black is clearly better.})
13... b4 14. Nd1 c3 {And the protected passed pawn gives Black a decisive
advantage.0-1 (40) Demin,V (2423)-Levin,F (2486) Oberhausen 2010[%csl Gc3]}) ({
Harmless is} 9. a4 a6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nd2 O-O $15 {With better position for
Black.}) ({White fails to obtain compensation after} 9. Nd2 a6 10. a4 Na5 11.
Be2 Bc6 {Let's see how the game could continue.} 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bf3 Bxf3 14.
gxf3 {And here, after} O-O (14... c6 15. Ke2 Be7 16. Rhg1 g6 (16... O-O 17. Bh6
Ne8) 17. h4 Nd5 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 (18... Qxe7 19. h5 Kd7) 19. Nce4 f5 $1 (19... Qc7
{1-0 (55) Thejkumar,M (2355)-Venkatesh,M (2451) New Delhi 2007}) 20. Nc5 e5 21.
h5 exd4 $19) 15. Rg1 c6 16. Nce4 Be7 {White runs out of attacking resources.})
9... Ba5 $1 {preserving the bishop is better than[%cal Gc6e7]} (9... Bxc3+ 10.
bxc3 O-O 11. a4 a6 12. Be2 Ne7 13. O-O {is improved version for white}) 10. Be2
(10. Ne5 Ne7 11. e4 Bc6 $1 $17 {1/2 (43) Lahno,K (2532) -Muminova,N (2293)
Tashkent 2013}) 10... Ne7 $1 {Now Black is planning to follow with Bc6, thus
establising a perfect coordination.[%cal Gd7c6]} 11. Bxf6 ({After} 11. O-O Nfd5
12. e4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 f6 14. Bf4 O-O 15. a4 a6 16. Rfd1 Bc6 $15 {White has only
slight compensation in view of the center control}) 11... gxf6 12. O-O Bc6 13.
e4 O-O 14. a4 a6 {And black has solid advantage. A typical line is} 15. d5 exd5
16. Nd4 Bb7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rfd1 Bxc3 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Qxc3 c6 {When White
has no compensation for the sacrificed material.} *

