1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 d5 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 dxc4 5. Bg5 Bb4 6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. a3 $1 {This
is White's best attempt to prove a compensation for the pawn. The idea is to
provoke the move 7...Bxc3 which helps White to strentghen his centre after
bxc3. Later on, Black will have much more difficulties to protect his c4-pawn.}
Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qd5 $1 {This is the most precise continuation. The c4-pawn
should be protected. Otherwise, White will enjoy a strong centre and a bishop
pair.} 9. Bxf6 {It's important to spoil Black's pawn structure since now black
king will never be complitely safe on the kingside.} ({Dubious is} 9. Bf4 {
Black could play} Bd7 10. Qc2 Qe4 11. Qc1 Na5 {Now after the following forced
sequence} 12. Bxc7 Nb3 13. Nd2 Qc6 14. Nxb3 cxb3 15. Bf4 Ne4 $1 {better than} (
15... a5 {which was played in the game Ftacnik,L (2350) -Lerner,K (2445) Stary
Smokovec 1977}) 16. Rb1 e5 17. Bxe5 f6 18. Bf4 Be6 $17 {Black is clearly
better.}) 9... gxf6 10. Nd2 $1 {This is the only chalenging idea.} ({In case of
} 10. g3 Bd7 11. Qc2 Na5 12. e4 Qc6 {Black could go for a long castle.[%cal
Ge8c8]}) ({After} 10. Qc2 {Black should prevent his opponent from gaining
space in the centre.[%cal Ge2e4]} f5 {With a sound position for Black. The
game might continue} 11. g3 b6 12. Bg2 Bb7 13. O-O (13. Nh4 Qa5 14. O-O O-O-O)
13... O-O-O $15 {black has pawn up and better position} 14. Nh4 (14. a4 Na5 15.
Rfb1 Qd6 (15... a6 16. Nh4 Qd6 17. e4 fxe4 18. Bxe4 Nb3 {0-1 (36) Vadasz,L 
(2375)-Lukacs,P (2440) Budapest 1996}) 16. Rb5 Nb3 17. Re1 a6 $17) (14. Ne5 $2
Qxg2+) 14... Qd7 (14... Qd6 {[%cal Gc6a5]} 15. e4) 15. e4 fxe4 16. Bxe4 Na5 {
Black was complitely fine in the game Kramnik,V-Ivanchuk,V/Wijk aan Zee 1999/})
10... b5 {White's main point was to provoke this move. Now the idea to make a
long castle is not that safe anymore.} 11. Qd1 {This seems to be the best
square for the queen since after e2-e3 or e2-e4, the queen could be
transferred to the kingside.} ({In case of} 11. Qc2 {, Black should protect
his b5-pawn by} a6 $1 {The play could follow with} 12. e4 Qd7 {When Black's
main idea is to attack the centre after Bb7 followed by Ne7 and c7-c5.[%cal
Gc6e7,Gc8b7,Gc7c5]} 13. f4 ({The advance} 13. a4 {is always well met by} Rb8 {
After} (13... b4 14. Bxc4) 14. Be2 b4 $1 15. O-O (15. Bxc4 bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qxd4)
(15. Nf3 Rg8 16. O-O b3 17. Qd2 e5 18. d5 Na5) 15... bxc3 16. Qxc3 Qxd4 {Black
is clearly better.}) 13... Bb7 14. Be2 Ne7 15. O-O c5 $1 {destroying the center
}) 11... a6 {keeping the option for 0-0-0 available} ({Interestiing is the
immediate counterattack with} 11... O-O $5 $146 12. a4 (12. e3 e5 13. Qh5 Ne7
14. Qh4 Bb7 15. Qxf6 Ng6 {and white is in big danger}) 12... b4 13. e4 Qg5 {
white should play with care to avoid the disaster[%csl Rc3,Rd4]}) 12. e4 Qd6
13. Qg4 (13. a4 Bb7 14. Qb1 O-O) 13... Bb7 14. Be2 (14. Qg7 Ke7) 14... O-O-O
15. O-O Rhg8 16. Qh3 Na5 17. Bf3 Qf4 18. Rad1 Nb3 {black is nearly winning} *

