{In this chapter I will cover the move 7.e5 which is the most popular
alternative to the main line.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4
Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. e5 cxd4 8. Qa4+ $1 {This is the only playable line for White.
He wants to develop his pieces as fast as possible. Now he is ready to follow
with 0-0-0.} ({The variation} 8. Nxd4 Qa5 $1 {leads to an equal position after
the forced sequence} 9. exf6 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxg5 11. fxg7 Qxg7 12. Qd2 ({The
attempt to immediately transfer the queen to the kingside doesn't promise
anything.} 12. Qf3 O-O 13. Bxc4 Nd7 14. Be2 {At this point, Black's simplest
way to the equality seem to be} e5 15. Nf5 Qf6 16. Qh5 Nc5 17. Ne3 Be6 18. O-O
b6 $11 {1-0 (38) Edouard,R (2659)-L'Ami,E (2618) Bogota COL 2014}) 12... O-O
13. Bxc4 Rd8 14. Qe3 Bd7 $1 {Important move. White is preapring 15...Nc6, thus
finishing the development and establishing a connection between the rooks.
Black's idea is to simplify the position and use White's structural defects in
the endgame.[%cal Gb8c6]} 15. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7g6,Gd7c6]} 16. Rad1 Nxd4
17. Rxd4 Bc6 18. f3 Rxd4 19. cxd4 Rd8 {White has no more chances to develop an
attack. On the other hand, the isolated pawn is already an weakness.}) ({
Premature is} 8. exf6 {since after} gxf6 {White g5-bishop is hanging. The game
Londyn,R - Kobo,O, 2016 followed} 9. Qa4+ ({The position arising after} 9. Nxd4
Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 fxg5 11. Bxc4 Nc6 12. O-O Bd7 13. Rb1 O-O 14. Qh5 Nxd4 15. cxd4
Qf6 16. d5 b6 {is slightly better for Black.}) 9... Nc6 10. O-O-O Bd7 11. Nxd4
Bxc3 12. Nxc6 fxg5 13. Qa3 (13. bxc3 Qc7) 13... Qf6 14. Rxd7 Kxd7 15. bxc3 Qf4+
16. Kb2 Qxf2+ {and Black is winning. 0-1 (18) Londyn,R (2401)-Kobo,O (2490)
Teplice CZE 2016}) 8... Nc6 9. O-O-O Bd7 10. Ne4 (10. exf6 $2 gxf6 11. Ne4 fxg5
$19) 10... Be7 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Bh4 {This is the critical position of the
entire variation. White has a piece for three pawns. Despite the doubled pawns
on the f-file Black controls all the important central squares. It's
interesting to point out that the black king is much more safer than the white
one because of the fact that he is protected by the central pawns. At this
point, I recommend} a6 $1 {Forcing White to take the c4-pawn with the queen.
Otherwise, b7-b5 is to follow. Later on, Black could develop an initiative
along the c-file.[%cal Gb7b5]} 13. Qxc4 e5 {Of course! After this move, Black
overtakes the initiative. He has a number of threats in this position. For
instance, now he wants to play Be6 followed by Rc8 and Nb4. White's queenside
is quite vulnerable.[%cal Gd7e6,Gc6b4,Ga8c8]} 14. Nxe5 {The only chance for
White is to give back the piece} ({The weak} 14. Kb1 $2 Be6 15. Qe2 Nb4 {was
seen in the game Rabadan - Kolev (look at the games section)}) ({After} 14.
Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd6+ Ke7 16. Nxb7 Qb6 {Black develops a dangerous initiative on
the queenside.}) 14... Nxe5 15. Qxd4 O-O $1 {I think that this is the best
continuation. Before starting active actions, we should complete the
development.} (15... Qc7+ 16. Kb1 Bf5 17. Be2 Rd8 18. Qe3 O-O 19. Rc1 {1/2 (24)
Babula,V (2548)-Rogozenco,D (2508) Bremen GER 2014}) 16. Be2 ({The premature} 
16. f4 {could be met by} Rc8+ 17. Nc3 (17. Kb1 $2 Bf5 $19) 17... Bc5 18. Qd5 (
18. Qd2 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2]} Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gc5e3]}) 18... Qb6 {Black attack seem
to be decisive. In case of} 19. fxe5 {just plays} Bf5 {with Be3 to follow.
[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc5e3]}) 16... Qc8+ 17. Kb1 ({To a better endgame for Black
leads the following forced sequence.} 17. Qc3 Bf5 18. Nxf6+ Kh8 19. g4 Be6 20.
Kb1 Qxc3 21. bxc3 Rac8 22. Kb2 Ng6 23. Bg5 h6 24. h4 Rfd8 25. f4 Rxd1 26. Bxd1
Nxf4 27. Bxf4 Bxf6 {Despite the reduced material, White king is still not safe.
[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6c3,Gc8c3,Gb7b5,Gb5b4]}) 17... Bf5 18. f3 Qe6 19. Ka1 ({The
attempt to win a pawn by means of} 19. Qd5 Rad8 20. Qxb7 {is quite risky. For
example} Rb8 21. Qxa6 (21. Qd5 Qb6 22. Qd4 Bc5 23. Qc3 Rfc8) 21... Rb6 {
Black's attack is quite dangerous.}) 19... Rac8 20. g4 (20. Rc1 Rc6) 20... Bg6
{[%cal Ge5c4]} 21. f4 $6 (21. Nc3 Rfd8 22. Qf4 b5 {In this position, Black is
the one who fights for an advantage.}) ({After} 21. Bg3 Rfd8 22. Qe3 Rxd1+ 23.
Rxd1 {[%csl Gf6,Gf7]} Nxg4 {Black is just a pawn up.}) 21... Rfd8 22. Qe3 Rxd1+
23. Rxd1 Nxg4 {[%csl Ge4]} 24. Bxg4 Qxg4 {White doesn't have compensation for
the pawn.[%csl Gd1]} *

