{From this chapter I am starting to cover the main line of Vienna game. We
will examine here the second popular move 10.Nb5. This line is not dangerous
for Black, but requires some concrete knowledge.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6
4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Nb5
{This move was the main line 30 years ago. Now it's considered to be quite
harmless.} ({More popular are the moves} 10. Bb5+ $1) ({and} 10. Bxf6 {which
are dealt with in the next files.}) 10... Nxe4 {Black should accept the
sacrifice because the calm 10...0-0 leads to a disaster} (10... O-O $2 11. Bxf6
gxf6 12. Qg4+ Kh8 13. Qh4 Nd7 14. Rd1 $18) 11. Qd4 (11. Bf4 $1 {Is much
serious try for White and will be covered in the next game.}) 11... O-O $1 {
This move saves the day.} 12. Qxe4 a6 13. Be7 {This is the only attempt which
allows White to keep the pressure.} ({In case of} 13. Bd3 {Black should react
with} f5 {when White is the one who should fight for an equality.} 14. Qb4 ({
Worse is} 14. Qe2 axb5 15. O-O Nc6 16. Bd2 $13 e5 17. Rfb1 Qc7 18. Rxb5 Be6 {
Black's position is perfectly comfortable. He has a strong centre and better
pawn structure.}) 14... axb5 15. Qxa5 (15. Bxb5 Nc6) 15... Rxa5 16. Be7 Re8 17.
Bb4 Ra8 18. Bxb5 Nc6 $10 {With equality.}) (13. Nd6 Qxg5 {and Black is already
better.}) (13. Nd4 {is not possible} Qxc3+ {White can resign}) 13... axb5 14.
Bb4 ({In case of} 14. Bxf8 Qxc3+ 15. Ke2 bxc4 16. Bd6 Qb2+ 17. Ke3 Nc6 {Black
has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 14... Qc7 15. Bxb5
({Accepting the exchange after} 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 $11 {leads to a draw by force.}
16. Bb3 (16. Bd3 Qxc3+ 17. Ke2 Qb2+ $44 18. Kf3 Nd7) (16. Bxb5 $2 Qxc3+ 17. Ke2
Qb2+ $19 18. Ke3 Qxb5) 16... Qxc3+ 17. Ke2 Qb2+ 18. Kf3 Qc3+ 19. Qe3 Qf6+ 20.
Qf4 (20. Ke2 Qb2+ 21. Kf3 {1/2 (23) Kempinski,R (2606)-Macieja,B (2614) Achaea
2012}) 20... Qc3+ 21. Ke2 Qb2+) 15... Bd7 $1 {insisting on exchange sacrifice}
(15... Rd8 {There is nothing wrong to keep the rook, but the text is stronger.}
16. O-O Bd7 $11) 16. Bxd7 (16. Bd3 f5 17. Qe3 (17. Qd4 Rd8 $15) 17... Re8 18.
O-O Nc6 19. f4 $2 (19. Bc5 Ne5 20. Be2 Ng4 21. Bxg4 fxg4 22. Rfe1 e5 $11) 19...
Nxb4 20. cxb4 Ra3 $1 $36 {With better position for Black. In the games section,
tou could find the game Litvinov,V (2368)-Kosyrev,V (2474) Minsk 2000}) 16...
Nxd7 17. Bxf8 Qxc3+ 18. Ke2 Qb2+ 19. Kf3 Nf6 20. Qb4 Qc2 {[%cal Ga8a4]} 21. g3
Qc6+ 22. Ke2 Rxf8 23. Rac1 Qg2 {Black has more than enough compensation for
the exchange. White's king is vulnerable in the centre and Black's practical
chances are preferable.} *

