1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Nb5 (10. Bb5+ $5) 10... Nxe4 11. Bf4 $1 {This
continuation is much stronger and requires more precision from Black. As a
compensation for the pawn, White has a strong pair of bishops. At the same
time, Black is behind in development and his knight is quite vulnerable in the
centre. Nevetheless, Black has enough resources to keep the balance.} O-O 12.
O-O {White should complete the development as soon as possible. The direct
attempts doesn't work.} ({For example} 12. Qf3 $6 {is well met by} Bd7) ({
while after} 12. Qd4 $2 Bd7 13. Nc7 Nc6 14. Qxe4 Qxc3+ {Black is winning.})
12... Nd7 $1 {Very precise move. Black is ready to support his e4-knight by
means of Ndf6. At the same time, the move 13.Qd4 could be met by 13...e5.} 13.
Re1 (13. Qd4 e5 14. Qxe4 ({The position after} 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 a6 16.
Qxe4 axb5 17. Bd5 Qxc3 {is just equal.}) 14... exf4 15. Qxf4 Nb6 16. Nd6 Nxc4
17. Qxc4 Be6 18. Qd4 Rfd8 19. Rfd1 Rd7 $11) (13. Nc7 $6 {Is a well known
mistake since after} e5 14. Nxa8 exf4 {Black is simply better here.}) 13...
Ndf6 {[%csl Gd6,Ge4][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6]} 14. a4 (14. Be5 Bd7) ({To a favorable
ending for Black leads} 14. Qd4 $5 Bd7 15. Nd6 Qxc3 16. Qxc3 Nxc3 17. Be5 Nfd5)
(14. Bc7 b6 15. Qd4 Ba6 16. a4 Bxb5 17. Bxb5 Rac8 18. Be5 a6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20.
Be2 Rfd8 {Black is much better.}) 14... Bd7 $1 $146 {After this new idea,
Black manages not only to solve his problems, but even to overtake the
initiative.} 15. Rxe4 ({It's already difficult to challenge the stability of
the e4-knight by means of} 15. Bd3 {since Black is just in time to support it
by} Bc6 {An interesting forced sequence arises after} 16. Qb1 Nc5 $1 17. Bc2 a6
18. Bc7 b6 19. Nd4 Ncd7 $3 {A fantastic idea that I managed to find in my
analysis. Despite the fact that White could capture the c6-bishop with a tempo,
he couldn't protect his pieces.} 20. Nxc6 Qc5 21. Ne7+ Qxe7 22. Qd1 Rfc8 23.
Bd6 Qd8 $15 {And Black has an extra pawn and much better pawn structure.})
15... Nxe4 16. Qxd7 a6 17. Na3 Qxc3 18. Qd1 Rac8 19. Qf1 Rfd8 $17 {Followed by
Qb2 and Nc3. White has serious problems here.[%cal Gc3b2,Ge4c3]} *

