1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bxf6 $5 {This move is not dangerous for Black if he
is well preapred. Nevertheless, White has garanteed draw in this line which is
impossible to prevent.} (10. Bb5+ Nbd7 $1 {main line}) 10... Qxc3+ 11. Kf1 gxf6
({A known mistake is} 11... Qxc4+ $2 12. Kg1 O-O 13. Qg4 {and White is winning.
}) 12. Rc1 (12. Bb5+ Nd7 13. h4 a6 {main line}) 12... Qa5 $1 {This is the only
move in the position.} 13. Nb5 ({After} 13. Bb5+ Ke7 $1 14. e5 {Black should
accept the draw which arises after} fxe5 15. Qh5 Nd7 16. Qg5+ Kf8 17. Rxc8+
Rxc8 18. Bxd7 Qd8 19. Nxe6+ fxe6 20. Qh6+ Kf7 21. Qxe6+ Kf8 22. Qh6+ $11 (22.
Qf5+)) (13. h4 $5 {This line is White's most dangerous try here and it is
analyzed in details in the next example.}) (13. Qg4 Nd7 $1 {I think that this
is Black's most precise reaction. Black protects his f6-pawn, thus preparing
himself for the future sacrifices on the e6-square.} ({The complications
arising after} 13... Ke7 14. Qg7 Rf8 15. e5 Qxe5 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Bxe6 Qg5 18.
Qxg5 fxg5 19. Bc8 Nd7 20. Bxb7 Rab8 21. Bd5 Rfc8 {Leads to equality.}) 14. Nxe6
(14. Qg7 Rf8) 14... fxe6 15. Qxe6+ Kd8 {and White will have hard time to prove
any compensation for the piece.}) ({Too slow is} 13. g3 {when Black manages to
comfortably develop his forces after} Bd7 {Typical idea for the Vienna
Variation. Black's next move will be 14...Nc6. The endgame arising after[%cal
Gb8c6]} 14. Kg2 Nc6 15. Bb5 O-O 16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Rxc6 Rfc8 19.
Qg4+ Qg5 20. Qxg5+ fxg5 21. Rhc1 Rxc6 22. Rxc6 Rb8 23. Ra6 Rb7 {is drawn.})
13... a6 $1 {This is the last precise move. White doesn't have enough
resources to create any problems for Black. After} 14. Nd6+ Ke7 15. h4 Rd8 16.
Nxc8+ Rxc8 {followed by Nd7, Black has quite decent position. I don't think
that White has sufficient compensation for the pawn.[%cal Gb8d7]} *

