1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bb5+ Nbd7 {The main line in Vienna variation.} (
10... Bd7 {This move leads to an advantage for White after:} 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12.
Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O a6 14. Rb1 Qc7 15. Qh5 Nc5 16. Rfe1 Qe5 17. Qh6 Qg5 18. Qh3
$14 {White's king is much safer than his opponent's. This allows White to have
a much easier play.}) 11. Bxf6 $1 {The only move which can pretend for the
advantage. White destroys his opponent's pawn structure and later will try to
use the exposed position of Black's king.} Qxc3+ $1 {Black should accept the
challenge.} (11... gxf6 12. O-O {And Black's position is hopeless. His King is
in danger, while White's is very safe on g1.}) 12. Kf1 gxf6 {We achieved the
most topical position in the Vienna game. Let's try to evaluate it. White has
the lead in developement and chances to organize an attack against Black's
king. His main problems are how to activate the rook from h1 and how to
arrange his other pieces in the optimal positions. The most usual plan is to
play h4 followed by Rh3. Later White try to penetrate Black's position with
the rooks at the open "c" or "d" files. The other typical attacking ideas are
the pawn sacrifice e4-e5 and Qd1-Qg4, followed by a piece sacrifice on e6. On
the other hand, Black has a pawn up which will be decisive factor in the
endgame. His only problem is to survive until then. Usually, Black wants to
develop his pieces in the following scheme: The safest square for the King is
e7, later the plan is to play a6, Ne(c)5 and to develop the bishop on d7, then
to activate his rooks. It is obvious that the Queen will be attack on c3, the
best square in this position for her will be d6} *

