1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bb5+ Nbd7 11. Bxf6 Qxc3+ 12. Kf1 gxf6 13. h4 a6 14.
Rh3 Qb4 $1 {The best move in this position} 15. Be2 (15. Rb3 Qd6 16. Bxd7+ Bxd7
17. Rxb7 Rd8 $11 {white return the pawn but lost the activity} 18. Kg1 Qe5 19.
Rc1 Qxe4 20. Rcc7 Rg8 21. Nf3 Qg4 22. g3 e5 23. Qd6 Qe6 24. Qc5 Rg4 $11) (15.
Ba4 $6 {here is not good} b5 16. Bb3 Bb7 {with better position for Black in
Kosic,D (2526)-Macieja,B (2594) Istanbul 2012} 17. Rc1 Qd6) (15. Rb1 Qd6 16.
Bxd7+ Bxd7 $1 (16... Qxd7 $2 17. Rd3 {1-0 (22) Maleki,N (2143)-Madiai,F (2227)
Erice ITA 2015}) 17. Rd3 Rd8 $11 18. Kg1 Bb5 19. Rd2 e5 {With better chances
for Black}) 15... Ne5 $1 {The most precise move order. We reach a critical
position for the whole line. White has at least 5 possible continuations, but
my analysis shows that Black has a good position after any of them.} (15... Qd6
{Black's defense is much more difficult after this move}) 16. Rc1 {Popular,
but not very strong move. Black has an easy game here. The plan is very simple
Qd6 followed by Bd7, Rd8 and even 0-0 in many occasions.} (16. h5 $5 {is
covered in the game.}) (16. Rb3 Qd6 17. Rc1 b5 18. Qd2 Bb7 19. Rd1 Rg8 {Black
continue development and has a threat of Ng4 and Bxe4.}) (16. f4 {Is premature
because of} Ng6 17. f5 exf5 18. exf5 Ne7 $15 {followed by castling and only
Black can be better here.}) (16. a4 $5 {is also covered in the next examples})
16... Qd6 $1 {Black's queen is come back to safety and pin the N on the d-file.
Our plan is to finish the developement with Bd7 and Rd8} 17. Rhc3 (17. Qd2 Bd7
18. Kg1 Rd8 19. Qb2 Ba4 20. Nf3 Bc6 21. Nxe5 Qxe5 22. Qxe5 fxe5 23. Bxa6 Bxe4
$15 {Black keeps the pawn up and has good chances to convert this endgame to a
full point. Degtiarev,E (2374)-Naumann,A (2258) Caleta 2010}) (17. Rc2 {leads
to a draw after} Bd7 18. Rd2 Qc7 19. Rc2 Qd6 (19... Nc6 $5 {can be a try to
continue the game.}) 20. Rd2 Qc7 21. Rc2 {1/2 (21) Grischuk,A (2746)-Kramnik,V
(2781) Moscow 2011}) 17... Bd7 18. g3 Rd8 19. f4 Nc6 20. Nb3 Qe7 $1 {Black is
playing for a win} ({The endgame is safe for White after:} 20... Qxd1+ 21. Rxd1
e5 22. Kf2 Ke7 23. Rb1 b5 24. Nc5 Nd4 25. Nxa6 Rc8 $11) 21. Qe1 O-O 22. Rc5 (
22. Qf2 e5 $1 $15 {taking d4 under control and activate the bishop}) 22... Rc8
23. Qf2 Rfd8 24. g4 e5 25. f5 a5 26. R5c3 a4 27. Nd2 Nd4 $17 {Black has a
material and positional advantage.} *

