1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bb5+ Nbd7 11. Bxf6 Qxc3+ 12. Kf1 gxf6 13. h4 a6 14.
Rh3 Qb4 $1 15. Be2 Ne5 $1 16. h5 $5 {An interesting idea that was played first
by Boris Gelfand himself. The best move in this position is} Qd6 $1 (16... Bd7
$2 17. Rb3 Qd6 18. Rxb7 {White has won the pawn back and has an advantage.})
17. Qd2 (17. Kg1 {White's attempt to bring the king to safety is too slow and
Black can obtain good play after:} Bd7 18. Rb1 Rd8 19. Rc3 b5 20. Rbc1 b4 21.
Rg3 Ke7 {Black is better in the game: Shulman,Y (2648)-Naiditsch,A (2697)
Montreal 2009}) 17... Nc6 18. Rd3 Qh2 19. f4 (19. Nf3 {Is an intersting try
here} Qh1+ 20. Ng1 Rg8 21. Rg3 Rxg3 22. fxg3 Bd7 $15 {Black's seems to be a
little bit better in this very complex position.}) 19... Rg8 20. Bf3 (20. g4 $6
{leads to a draw after:} Qh1+ 21. Kf2 Qh4+ $11) 20... Bd7 $1 21. Ne2 ({If} 21.
Nb3 Ne5 $1 {Nice tactics that saves the day for Black.} 22. fxe5 Bb5 23. a4 (
23. Rd1 $6 {Is not good here, because of:} Rd8 24. Nc1 Qxe5 {And Black is
better}) 23... Bxd3+ 24. Qxd3 Rd8 25. Qc3 {Black has a choice to keep the
queens or to play an endgame, both possibilities are about equal, so I leave
to you the choice - which move appeals more to your style.} fxe5 $11 {With
both kings in the centre both sides keep their chances. It seems to me that
Black's play is a bit easier.} (25... Qxe5 26. Qxe5 fxe5 27. Nc5 Rc8 28. Nxb7
Ke7 {Black is at least not worse here.})) 21... Qh1+ 22. Ng1 Nd4 $1 {Fantastik
resource for Black!} 23. Rxd4 Bb5+ 24. Kf2 Qh4+ 25. Ke3 e5 $1 $11 {With a
perpetual soon. The rest of the game you can find in the games section.} *

