1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bb5+ Nbd7 11. Bxf6 Qxc3+ 12. Kf1 gxf6 13. h4 a6 14.
Rh3 Qb4 $1 15. Be2 Ne5 $1 16. a4 $5 {This move looks a bit slow for me.} (16.
Rb1 {The most topical move in this variation. Keep in mind this game. I expect
new games in this line in the near future.} Qd6 17. Qd2 Bd7 {Black gives back
the pawn to complete the development.} 18. Rxb7 Bb5 {Black is sacrificing a
pawn for activating his pieces. It is obvious that this move and the following
variation is part of the deep home preparation of top GM Levon Aronian.} 19.
Rb3 Rc8 $1 {Another precise move.} 20. Bxb5+ axb5 21. Qb4 {White forced
exchanging queens and get rid of the nasty pin on the d-file.} Qxb4 22. Rxb4
O-O $1 23. R7xb5 Rfd8 {In first sight the position looks hard for Black, but
after you analyzed it deeper you can find easier that Black activity
compensate the missing pawn.} 24. Ke2 Kg7 {You can find the rest of the game
in games section. Black's plan is very easy to find: just play Rc3-Ra3 next
moves and start giving checks. 1/2 (36) Giri (2773)-Aronian (2780) Stavanger
NOR 2015}) 16... Qd6 17. Qd2 (17. Rb1 Bd7 18. Rxb7 Rd8 {White regains the pawn,
but Black completes the developement.}) 17... Nc6 $1 {Black uses the pin on
the d-file.} 18. Rd3 Qh2 {threatening mate in [%emt 0:00:01]} 19. f4 $5 Rg8 {
this is the safer choice.} (19... Nxd4 {Is another way to reach a playable
position.} 20. Rh3 $1 (20. Rxd4 $2 O-O {Black is just better here.}) 20... Qxh3
21. gxh3 Nb3 22. Qc3 Nxa1 23. Qxa1 e5 {With a very complex endgame.}) 20. Bf3
Kf8 21. Nxc6 {with a forced draw after:} bxc6 22. Rd8+ Kg7 23. Rxg8+ Kxg8 $11
24. e5 $1 Qh1+ 25. Kf2 Qxa1 26. Qd8+ Kg7 27. Qxf6+ {with perpetual check.} *

