1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bg5 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Bxf6 Qxc3+ 11. Kf1 gxf6 12. Rc1 Qa5 $1 13. h4 $1 {
The most dangerous continuation.} Ke7 $1 14. Rh3 (14. Nb5 {Is well met by:} Rd8
15. Qh5 Nd7 ({but not} 15... Nc6 $4 16. Qc5+ {And White wins in the game: 1-0 
(28) Lesiege,A (2564)-Bolduc,S Montreal 2001}) 16. Bxe6 Ne5 17. Rc7+ Bd7 {And
Black's Knight dominates the position. Suddenlty all White's pieces are
hanging. Georgiev,V (2515)-Wells,P (2495) Regensburg 1997}) (14. Qg4 $5 {Is a
very dangerous try.} Rd8 (14... Nc6 $1 {is the best choice here, with
transposition to the main lines.}) 15. e5 Qxe5 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 {a mistake which
leads to a hard position for Black.} 17. Bxe6 fxe6 (17... Rd4 18. Qf3 Nc6 19.
Re1 {White is much better in the game: Vallejo Pons,F (2554)-Sedlak,N (2423)
Aviles 2000}) 18. Qg7+ Ke8 $11 19. Qg8+ Ke7 20. Qxh7+ Ke8 21. Rh3 $1 {And
White is much better.}) (14. Nb3 {Is not dangerous for Black} Qe5 15. Qd2 Rd8
16. Qe3 Bd7 17. Rh3 Bc6 $15) 14... Nc6 $1 ({Pay attention that the most
popular move here:} 14... Rd8 $6 {Is inacuracy, because of} 15. Re3 ({even
immediate} 15. Nf5+ $5 {is not bad} exf5 16. Qh5 {and White wins a nice game
in Janssen,R (2498)-Lauber,A (2497) Germany 2011}) 15... Rd6 (15... Nc6 {is
not helping much, because of} 16. Nf5+ exf5 17. exf5+ Ne5 18. Qh5 Kd6 19. Bxf7
Nc6 20. Qxh7 $16 {White's attack seems very dangerous to me.}) 16. Nf5+ {
unpleasant surprise} exf5 17. exf5+ Kd7 18. Be6+ {Black can resign in the
recent game: Gagare,S (2491)-Kuzubov,Y (2638) Dubai UAE 2016}) 15. Nxc6+ (15.
Nf5+ {is not working now.} exf5 16. exf5 Ne5 17. Re3 Bxf5 {With advantage for
Black.}) 15... bxc6 16. Rd3 (16. Kg1 {is a bit slow} Rd8 17. Qb3 Rd4 18. Bf1
Bd7 19. Rd3 c5 {Black is fine}) ({After} 16. Rhc3 Rd8 17. Qf3 Rd4 18. Bb3 Bd7 {
Black's position is completely sound.}) 16... Rd8 17. Rxd8 (17. e5 {is not so
dangerous here.} fxe5 18. Rxd8 Qxd8) 17... Qxd8 18. Qh5 (18. Qf3 {Is well met
by} Qc7 19. Kg1 Bd7 20. Bb3 Rb8 {White has some compensation for the missing
pawn, but not more than that. 0-1 (29) Pakhomov,E (2353)-Stukopin,A (2380)
Dagomys 2009}) 18... Qd4 19. Kg1 (19. Qxh7 {Was played by Anatoly Karpov
without much success} Rb8 20. Bb3 Ba6+ 21. Kg1 Bd3 {1/2 (30) Karpov,A (2755)
-Huebner,R (2605) Skelleftea 1989}) (19. Be2 Rb8 $1 {Despite the bad result
Black was better in the game: 1-0 (29) Dreev,A (2485)-Janjgava,L (2425)
Vilnius 1988}) 19... Rb8 20. Bb3 Rb4 $1 (20... Qxe4 {was played in the game 1/
2 (26) Gleizerov,E (2405)-Sorokin,M (2400) Voronezh 1988}) (20... Bd7 {is
played in the recent game between Dzagnidze,N (2535)-Batsiashvili,N (2476)
Batumi GEO 2016}) 21. Rxc6 (21. Qxh7 Qxe4 22. Qxe4 Rxe4 23. Rxc6 {The endgame
is safe for Black.}) 21... Bd7 22. Rc7 ({White can try} 22. Rc1 Qe5 {Ostrowski,
L (2355)-Ivanov,S (2460) Bydgoszcz 1990}) 22... Qd6 $1 ({Black can enter the
drawish endgame by:} 22... Qa1+ $146 23. Kh2 Qe5+ {1/2 (27) Relange,E (2459)
-Delorme,A (2441) Guingamp 2010}) 23. Rxa7 Rxe4 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Ge4e1]} 24.
Qa5 Re5 {With an equal position in the game. Dreev,A (2495)-Yudasin,L (2505)
Simferopol 1988} *

